From Soup: 0 Chem. Soc. Rev.
 ###### 
From cou.: 1 Biophysical phenomena related to cellular biochemistry and transport are spatially and temporally dynamic, and are directly involved in the regulation of physiology at the sub-cellular to tissue spatial scale. Real time monitoring of transmembrane transport provides information about the physiology and viability of cells, tissues, and organisms. Combining information learned from real time transport studies with genomics and proteomics allows us to better understand the functional and mechanistic aspects of cellular and sub-cellular systems. To accomplish this, ultrasensitive sensing technologies are required to probe this functional realm of biological systems with high temporal and spatial resolution. In addition to ongoing research aimed at developing new and enhanced sensors (e.g., increased sensitivity, enhanced analyte selectivity, reduced response time, and novel microfabrication approaches), work over the last few decades has advanced sensor utility through new sensing modalities that extend and enhance the data recorded by sensors. A microsensor technique based on phase sensitive detection of real time biophysical transport is reviewed here. The self-referencing technique converts non-invasive extracellular concentration sensors into dynamic flux sensors for measuring transport from the membrane to the tissue scale. In this tutorial review, we discuss the use of self-referencing micro/nanosensors for measuring physiological activity of living cells/tissues in agricultural, environmental, and biomedical applications comprehensible to any scientist/engineer.
From Soup: 1 Biophysical phenomena related to cellular biochemistry and transport are spatially and temporally dynamic, and are directly involved in the regulation of physiology at the sub-cellular to tissue spatial scale. Real time monitoring of transmembrane transport provides information about the physiology and viability of cells, tissues, and organisms. Combining information learned from real time transport studies with genomics and proteomics allows us to better understand the functional and mechanistic aspects of cellular and sub-cellular systems. To accomplish this, ultrasensitive sensing technologies are required to probe this functional realm of biological systems with high temporal and spatial resolution. In addition to ongoing research aimed at developing new and enhanced sensors ( e.g. , increased sensitivity, enhanced analyte selectivity, reduced response time, and novel microfabrication approaches), work over the last few decades has advanced sensor utility through new sensing modalities that extend and enhance the data recorded by sensors. A microsensor technique based on phase sensitive detection of real time biophysical transport is reviewed here. The self-referencing technique converts non-invasive extracellular concentration sensors into dynamic flux sensors for measuring transport from the membrane to the tissue scale. In this tutorial review , we discuss the use of self-referencing micro/nanosensors for measuring physiological activity of living cells/tissues in agricultural, environmental, and biomedical applications comprehensible to any scientist/engineer.
 ###### 
From cou.: 2 Cells utilize a combination of genetic and physiological mechanisms for survival. Membrane transport across organelles (e.g., mitochondria/chloroplast, nucleus) and/or across the outer cell wall regulates growth, metabolism, bioenergetics, stress signaling, immune response, and morphology. Cells contain a diverse array of innate molecular mechanisms capable of sensing extracellular and/or intracellular molecules, and regulate transport mechanisms accordingly. In many ways, physiological transport mechanisms are the primary system which protect the genome from damage. Sensitive and robust technologies are needed which are capable of sensing real time changes in biophysical transport across cell membranes and/or organelles. These technologies must not only be highly sensitive and selective, but must also be minimally invasive and intrusive, enabling real time quantification of cell membrane transport with minimal physical and chemical effect(s) on cell behavior. This broadly defines the motive of physiological sensing, and this review will focus on tools for quantifying real time biophysical transport in the cell, tissue, organ, and whole organism spatial domains. Tools for characterizing morphological phenomena, though equally important, will not be covered.
From Soup: 2 Cells utilize a combination of genetic and physiological mechanisms for survival. Membrane transport across organelles ( e.g. , mitochondria/chloroplast, nucleus ) and/or across the outer cell wall regulates growth, metabolism, bioenergetics, stress signaling, immune response, and morphology. Cells contain a diverse array of innate molecular mechanisms capable of sensing extracellular and/or intracellular molecules, and regulate transport mechanisms accordingly. In many ways, physiological transport mechanisms are the primary system which protect the genome from damage. Sensitive and robust technologies are needed which are capable of sensing real time changes in biophysical transport across cell membranes and/or organelles. These technologies must not only be highly sensitive and selective, but must also be minimally invasive and intrusive, enabling real time quantification of cell membrane transport with minimal physical and chemical effect(s) on cell behavior. This broadly defines the motive of physiological sensing, and this review will focus on tools for quantifying real time biophysical transport in the cell, tissue, organ, and whole organism spatial domains. Tools for characterizing morphological phenomena, though equally important, will not be covered.
 ###### 
From cou.: 3 Electroanalytical chemistry and optics have been utilized for decades in the development of sensors for measuring intracellular and extracellular analytes (reviewed by numerous authors.1–5 Molecules that are directly relevant to metabolism (e.g., oxygen, adenosine triphosphate), homeostasis (e.g., H+, Na+, K+, Ca2+), and cell signaling (e.g., nitric oxide, glutamate, dopamine) can be measured using these techniques. Ideally, sensors should introduce little or no physical/chemical interference on physiological transport, which potentially leads to membrane damage and/or cytotoxicity.
From Soup: 3 Electroanalytical chemistry and optics have been utilized for decades in the development of sensors for measuring intracellular and extracellular analytes (reviewed by numerous authors. 1–5 Molecules that are directly relevant to metabolism ( e.g. , oxygen, adenosine triphosphate ), homeostasis ( e.g. , H + , Na + , K + , Ca 2+ ), and cell signaling ( e.g. , nitric oxide, glutamate , dopamine ) can be measured using these techniques. Ideally, sensors should introduce little or no physical/chemical interference on physiological transport, which potentially leads to membrane damage and/or cytotoxicity.
 ###### 
From cou.: 4 Techniques for monitoring the concentration of intracellular analyte(s) and protein expression/activity include: fluorescent indicator dyes,6,7 patch clamp,8 and micro/nano probes.9 Challenges when using fluorescent dyes include cytoxicity, organelle sequestration, and intracellular buffering.10 Disadvantages of using patch clamp and/or intracellular micro/nano probes includes physical damage to cell membrane(s),11 and sensor fouling.
From Soup: 4 Techniques for monitoring the concentration of intracellular analyte (s) and protein expression/activity include: fluorescent indicator dyes , 6,7 patch clamp, 8 and micro/nano probes. 9 Challenges when using fluorescent dyes include cytoxicity, organelle sequestration, and intracellular buffering. 10 Disadvantages of using patch clamp and/or intracellular micro/nano probes includes physical damage to cell membrane(s), 11 and sensor fouling.
 ###### 
From cou.: 5 Extracellular tools for measuring analyte concentration include micro to nanoscale probes,12 lab on chip/biochip devices,13 microwell approaches,14 and microdialysis.15 These technologies have been highly useful and provided a wealth of information, but many suffer from significant signal drift/noise and temporal restraints. While assays and chip-based devices are capable of extremely high throughput and real time analysis,14,16 subtle changes in analyte concentration are often lost to signal noise/drift, and real time quantification of membrane transport is not currently possible. Though recent techniques have overcome many of the temporal and sensitivity limitations associated with assays, large sample sizes (or small sample volumes) are required for time resolved measurements, which is often not representative of physiological conditions.
From Soup: 5 Extracellular tools for measuring analyte concentration include micro to nanoscale probes, 12 lab on chip/biochip devices, 13 microwell approaches, 14 and microdialysis . 15 These technologies have been highly useful and provided a wealth of information, but many suffer from significant signal drift/noise and temporal restraints. While assays and chip-based devices are capable of extremely high throughput and real time analysis, 14,16 subtle changes in analyte concentration are often lost to signal noise/drift, and real time quantification of membrane transport is not currently possible. Though recent techniques have overcome many of the temporal and sensitivity limitations associated with assays, large sample sizes (or small sample volumes) are required for time resolved measurements, which is often not representative of physiological conditions.
