From cou.: 6 In addition to novel fabrication approaches, research in advanced materials (e.g., nanomaterials) has greatly enhanced the signal transduction capabilities of sensors,17,18 and many biocompatible materials have been developed which reduce the release of harmful/deleterious molecules from sensors.19 These advancements have allowed wide use of sensors and biosensors in applications which were not economically or technically feasible a few decades ago. However, measurement in the environment near living cells remains challenging, and damaged cells and/or sensors continue to produce erroneous results.
From Soup: 6 In addition to novel fabrication approaches, research in advanced materials ( e.g. , nanomaterials) has greatly enhanced the signal transduction capabilities of sensors, 17,18 and many biocompatible materials have been developed which reduce the release of harmful/deleterious molecules from sensors. 19 These advancements have allowed wide use of sensors and biosensors in applications which were not economically or technically feasible a few decades ago. However, measurement in the environment near living cells remains challenging, and damaged cells and/or sensors continue to produce erroneous results.
 ###### 
From cou.: 7 The ultimate goal for all physiological sensors is to quantify analyte concentration and/or transport while causing little or no physical/chemical interaction with cells. This remains a very difficult technical challenge, and non-invasive (or minimally intrusive) physiological sensors are currently only developed and used in a few labs, rather than being a standardized method.
From Soup: 7 The ultimate goal for all physiological sensors is to quantify analyte concentration and/or transport while causing little or no physical/chemical interaction with cells. This remains a very difficult technical challenge, and non-invasive (or minimally intrusive) physiological sensors are currently only developed and used in a few labs, rather than being a standardized method.
 ###### 
From cou.: 8 One non-invasive sensing modality for measuring analyte transport utilizes a self-referencing (SR) approach.11,20,21 Current state of the art SR technologies combine ultrasensitive minimally-invasive sensor technologies with advanced modalities to extend and enhance the data recorded by the sensor. Acquisition and amplification of differential signals significantly improves sensitivity, selectivity, and signal-to-noise ratio, allowing these tools to be used in non-invasive (or minimally intrusive) formats.10,20,21,23,24
From Soup: 8 One non-invasive sensing modality for measuring analyte transport utilizes a self-referencing (SR) approach. 11,20,21 Current state of the art SR technologies combine ultrasensitive minimally-invasive sensor technologies with advanced modalities to extend and enhance the data recorded by the sensor. Acquisition and amplification of differential signals significantly improves sensitivity, selectivity, and signal-to-noise ratio, allowing these tools to be used in non-invasive (or minimally intrusive) formats. 10,20,21,23,24
 ###### 
From cou.: 9 SR techniques have been used to measure intracellular analyte concentration.22–24 One of the most promising of these SR devices are minimally invasive intracellular probes known as MOONs,24 which are magnetically modulated optical nanosensors designed for monitoring intracellular chemical and physical processes. Although these state of the art techniques will no doubt facilitate major advancements in cell biology, adaptation of the technology for use in the extracellular environment is difficult or impossible due to buffering, dilution, and background interference.
From Soup: 9 SR techniques have been used to measure intracellular analyte concentration. 22–24 One of the most promising of these SR devices are minimally invasive intracellular probes known as MOONs, 24 which are magnetically modulated optical nanosensors designed for monitoring intracellular chemical and physical processes. Although these state of the art techniques will no doubt facilitate major advancements in cell biology, adaptation of the technology for use in the extracellular environment is difficult or impossible due to buffering, dilution, and background interference.
 ###### 
From cou.: 10 For non-invasive measurement of extracellular transport, Jaffe and Nuccitelli20 developed the first vibrating probe technique in 1974 (capable of detecting bioelectric currents as small as 10 nA cm−2 s−1). This SR technique has since been extended and enhanced for use with a wide range of electrochemical and optical micro/nanosensors for real time measurement of trans-membrane (or trans-tissue) transport in neurobiology,26 plant physiology,27–29 entomology,30 developmental biology,28 biofilm physiology,31–33 ecotoxicology,34 and various other applications.35
From Soup: 10 For non-invasive measurement of extracellular transport, Jaffe and Nuccitelli 20 developed the first vibrating probe technique in 1974 (capable of detecting bioelectric currents as small as 10 nA cm −2 s −1 ). This SR technique has since been extended and enhanced for use with a wide range of electrochemical and optical micro/nanosensors for real time measurement of trans -membrane (or trans -tissue) transport in neurobiology, 26 plant physiology, 27–29 entomology, 30 developmental biology, 28 biofilm physiology, 31–33 ecotoxicology, 34 and various other applications. 35
 ###### 
From cou.: 11 The SR microsensor technique converts static micro/nanosensors with otherwise low signal-to-noise ratios into dynamic flux sensors capable of filtering out signals not associated with biologically active transport. The technique is based on Fick's first law of diffusion (eqn (1)), and uses phase sensitive detection to “self-correct” for signals produced by ambient drift and noise. This is done by oscillating a single micro/nanosensor between two locations using stepper motors.20 The current technique uses a DC coupled move-wait-measure technique for detection of real time changes in differential analyte concentration (ΔC) over a fixed excursion distance (ΔX) (Fig. 1).
From Soup: 11 The SR microsensor technique converts static micro/nanosensors with otherwise low signal-to-noise ratios into dynamic flux sensors capable of filtering out signals not associated with biologically active transport. The technique is based on Fick's first law of diffusion ( eqn (1) ), and uses phase sensitive detection to “self-correct” for signals produced by ambient drift and noise. This is done by oscillating a single micro/nanosensor between two locations using stepper motors. 20 The current technique uses a DC coupled move-wait-measure technique for detection of real time changes in differential analyte concentration (Δ C ) over a fixed excursion distance (Δ X ) ( Fig. 1 ).
