From Soup: 22 If Δ C /Δ X is continuously measured, real time measurement of biophysical flux may be obtained. Typically, position x is within 1–2 μm of the biological specimen of interest, and a sensor is translated in the direction perpendicular to the tangent of the surface) ( Fig. 1B ). The majority of transmembrane transport occurs along this vector, and if the excursion distance (Δ X ) is within the linear portion of the concentration gradient ( see Fig. 5 and related discussion ), Fick's first law of diffusion may be used to directly calculate flux based on measured values of Δ C /Δ X . Multi-dimension measurements ( i.e. , square wave oscillation) are possible, 36 although this approach should be reserved for highly specialized applications due to temporal limitations.
 ###### 
From cou.: 23 If ΔC/ΔX is continuously measured, real time measurement of biophysical flux may be obtained. Typically, position x is within 1–2 μm of the biological specimen of interest, and a sensor is translated in the direction perpendicular to the tangent of the surface) (Fig. 1B). The majority of transmembrane transport occurs along this vector, and if the excursion distance (ΔX) is within the linear portion of the concentration gradient (seeFig. 5and related discussion), Fick's first law of diffusion may be used to directly calculate flux based on measured values of ΔC/ΔX. Multi-dimension measurements (i.e., square wave oscillation) are possible,36 although this approach should be reserved for highly specialized applications due to temporal limitations.
From Soup: 23 A brief description of SR sensor fabrication is provided below (organized by transduction type), followed by a description of hardware, governing equations/theory, and demonstration of recent biomedical, agricultural, and bioenvironmental applications.
