From cou.: 24 A brief description of SR sensor fabrication is provided below (organized by transduction type), followed by a description of hardware, governing equations/theory, and demonstration of recent biomedical, agricultural, and bioenvironmental applications.
From Soup: 24 For all recognition/transduction schemes, sensors are commonly compared in regard to sensitivity, selectivity, and durability using common methods. 1,37 This review will cover electrochemical and optical self-referencing microsensors (including both amperometric and potentiometric electrochemical sensors). All discussion is organized following the recognition-transduction-acquisition scheme commonly used. 3,37 Further details on the mechanisms and governing theory of optical and electrochemical sensors may be found in the literature and references therein.
 ###### 
From cou.: 25 For all recognition/transduction schemes, sensors are commonly compared in regard to sensitivity, selectivity, and durability using common methods.1,37 This review will cover electrochemical and optical self-referencing microsensors (including both amperometric and potentiometric electrochemical sensors). All discussion is organized following the recognition-transduction-acquisition scheme commonly used.3,37 Further details on the mechanisms and governing theory of optical and electrochemical sensors may be found in the literature and references therein.
From Soup: 25 Amperometric microsensors 1 have been utilized for a wide range of analytes in various formats. Electrochemical amperometry utilizes oxidizing or reducing currents for detection of electroactive species ( e.g. , H 2 O 2 , NO, NADH). A significant fraction of recent amperometric sensor research has focused on incorporation of biological recognition elements in sensors ( i.e. , amperometric biosensors). A glucose biosensor ( Fig. 2 ) is used for demonstrating the working mechanism of enzyme-based amperometric biosensors. Recognition involves chemical binding of glucose in the enzyme pocket of glucose oxidase (GOx). Glucose is subsequently oxidized by GOx, consuming oxygen and producing gluconic acid and H 2 O 2 . The H 2 O 2 is detected using oxidative amperometry (positive polarization potential). The oxidized glucose : hydrogen peroxide ratio is 1 : 1, and the measured current is used to determine the concentration of glucose near the sensor tip. 35 Examples of enzymatic biosensors (and the respective enzyme) include : glucose ( glucose oxidase), 35 glutamate ( glutamate oxidase), 12,26 and ethanol / methanol ( alcohol oxidase). 38 One of the major advantages of a biosensor over a chemical sensor is the high degree of selectivity, although problems such as non-specific binding are troublesome. 39
 ###### 
From cou.: 26 Amperometric microsensors1 have been utilized for a wide range of analytes in various formats. Electrochemical amperometry utilizes oxidizing or reducing currents for detection of electroactive species (e.g., H2O2, NO, NADH). A significant fraction of recent amperometric sensor research has focused on incorporation of biological recognition elements in sensors (i.e., amperometric biosensors). A glucose biosensor (Fig. 2) is used for demonstrating the working mechanism of enzyme-based amperometric biosensors. Recognition involves chemical binding of glucose in the enzyme pocket of glucose oxidase (GOx). Glucose is subsequently oxidized by GOx, consuming oxygen and producing gluconic acid and H2O2. The H2O2 is detected using oxidative amperometry (positive polarization potential). The oxidized glucose:hydrogen peroxide ratio is 1:1, and the measured current is used to determine the concentration of glucose near the sensor tip.35 Examples of enzymatic biosensors (and the respective enzyme) include: glucose (glucose oxidase),35glutamate (glutamate oxidase),12,26 and ethanol/methanol (alcohol oxidase).38 One of the major advantages of a biosensor over a chemical sensor is the high degree of selectivity, although problems such as non-specific binding are troublesome.39
From Soup: 26 Details on fabrication of amperometric sensors/biosensors can be found in the literature. 21,26,35,40 Amperometric sensors/biosensors typically utilize a highly conductive metal ( e.g. , platinum, gold) either in a cylindrical (wire) 21,35 or planar geometry. Sensitivity is directly related to enzyme activity and the active surface area over which the polarization potential is applied. Enzyme immobilization techniques include avidin/biotin linkages, gold/ thiol linkages, 41 and bovine serum albumin-gluteraldehyde linking. 41,43 Nanomaterials have been shown to significantly increase signal output in a wide variety of sensor and biosensor designs due to enhanced electron transfer via quantum effects. 17 Thus, incorporation of nanomaterials has recently become commonplace for enhancing electrocatalysis. Examples of common nanomaterials immobilized in sensors include amorphous nanoclusters ( e.g. , platinum), 17,21,35 carbon nanotubes (CNT), 17 and metallic nanomaterials ( e.g. , gold, silver, titanium). 42
 ###### 
From cou.: 27 Details on fabrication of amperometric sensors/biosensors can be found in the literature.21,26,35,40 Amperometric sensors/biosensors typically utilize a highly conductive metal (e.g., platinum, gold) either in a cylindrical (wire)21,35 or planar geometry. Sensitivity is directly related to enzyme activity and the active surface area over which the polarization potential is applied. Enzyme immobilization techniques include avidin/biotin linkages, gold/thiol linkages,41 and bovine serum albumin-gluteraldehyde linking.41,43 Nanomaterials have been shown to significantly increase signal output in a wide variety of sensor and biosensor designs due to enhanced electron transfervia quantum effects.17 Thus, incorporation of nanomaterials has recently become commonplace for enhancing electrocatalysis. Examples of common nanomaterials immobilized in sensors include amorphous nanoclusters (e.g., platinum),17,21,35carbon nanotubes (CNT),17 and metallic nanomaterials (e.g., gold, silver, titanium).42
From Soup: 27 Potentiometric microsensors are most commonly used to detect ion activity via measurement of electromotive force between two electrochemical half-cells with zero applied voltage. 1,37 These ion-selective electrodes ( ISE ) have been used in a wide range of formats, and this review will focus on micro ISE (μISE) utilizing liquid phase ion-selective membranes.
 ###### 
From cou.: 28 Potentiometric microsensors are most commonly used to detect ion activity via measurement of electromotive force between two electrochemical half-cells with zero applied voltage.1,37 These ion-selective electrodes (ISE) have been used in a wide range of formats, and this review will focus on micro ISE (μISE) utilizing liquid phase ion-selective membranes.
From Soup: 28 Activity of target ions is recognized by an ionophore ( e.g. , neutral carrier or ion exchanger) immobilized in a porous membrane. Following electrochemical equilibrium with the local microenvironment, a potential difference develops between the membrane and an external reference electrode which is log-dependent on the activity of the target ion. This potential is transduced into a voltage signal by an electron exchange reaction at the surface of a Ag/AgCl wire immersed in the electrolyte on the back side of the ISE membrane. The log-dependent relationship is described by the Nernst (or Nikolsky–Eisenmann) equation. 37
 ###### 
From cou.: 29 Activity of target ions is recognized by an ionophore (e.g., neutral carrier or ion exchanger) immobilized in a porous membrane. Following electrochemical equilibrium with the local microenvironment, a potential difference develops between the membrane and an external reference electrode which is log-dependent on the activity of the target ion. This potential is transduced into a voltage signal by an electron exchange reaction at the surface of a Ag/AgCl wire immersed in the electrolyte on the back side of the ISE membrane. The log-dependent relationship is described by the Nernst (or Nikolsky–Eisenmann) equation.37
From Soup: 29 A potassium-selective microelectrode is used to demonstrate the recognition-transduction mechanism for an ISE ( Fig. 3 ). Potassium ions in the liquid near the tip of the microelectrode interact with valinomycin within a liquid ion exchange membrane (LIX). The potassium- ionophore reaction causes a change in electromotive force, which is transduced to a measurable voltage via a reaction on the surface of an electroplated Ag/AgCl wire immersed in electrolyte. ISE potential is recorded as a voltage against a reference electrode.
 ###### 
From cou.: 30 A potassium-selective microelectrode is used to demonstrate the recognition-transduction mechanism for an ISE (Fig. 3). Potassium ions in the liquid near the tip of the microelectrode interact with valinomycin within a liquid ion exchange membrane (LIX). The potassium-ionophore reaction causes a change in electromotive force, which is transduced to a measurable voltage via a reaction on the surface of an electroplated Ag/AgCl wire immersed in electrolyte. ISE potential is recorded as a voltage against a reference electrode.
From Soup: 30 Details on fabrication of μISE utilizing liquid membranes may be found in the referenced literature. 31,44 Microelectrodes are typically constructed using non-filamented, tapered, silanized glass capillaries. Capillaries are backfilled with electrolyte and subsequently front filled with ion exchange cocktail. Microelectrodes are inserted into a half-cell microelectrode holder fitted with an electrolytically plated Ag/AgCl wire, and potential measured against a reference electrode (commonly 3 M KCl with 3% agar). Recently, monolithic microelectrodes have been developed, 45 but have not yet been used in SR modality.
 ###### 
From cou.: 31 Details on fabrication of μISE utilizing liquid membranes may be found in the referenced literature.31,44 Microelectrodes are typically constructed using non-filamented, tapered, silanized glass capillaries. Capillaries are backfilled with electrolyte and subsequently front filled with ion exchange cocktail. Microelectrodes are inserted into a half-cell microelectrode holder fitted with an electrolytically plated Ag/AgCl wire, and potential measured against a reference electrode (commonly 3 M KCl with 3% agar). Recently, monolithic microelectrodes have been developed,45 but have not yet been used in SR modality.
From Soup: 31 Optical microsensors have many advantages over electrochemical sensors, including reduced susceptibility to fouling, low temperature dependence, low drift/noise, immunity to electromagnetic interference, no requirement of a reference electrode (the leading source of signal artifact in electrochemical sensing), and enhanced sensitivity due to peripheral optical components with single photon sensitivity. 46,47 There are many measurement techniques for developing optical sensors, including absorption, total internal reflection, fluorescence, and surface plasmon resonance . 48 Fiber optic sensors are commonly used in microsensor formats as single fiber, or bundled fibers. Fiber optics are capable of transmitting light over long distances and multiplexing, but can be subject to background absorbance, fluorescence/Raman scattering, and diffraction effects.
 ###### 
From cou.: 32 Optical microsensors have many advantages over electrochemical sensors, including reduced susceptibility to fouling, low temperature dependence, low drift/noise, immunity to electromagnetic interference, no requirement of a reference electrode (the leading source of signal artifact in electrochemical sensing), and enhanced sensitivity due to peripheral optical components with single photon sensitivity.46,47 There are many measurement techniques for developing optical sensors, including absorption, total internal reflection, fluorescence, and surface plasmon resonance.48 Fiber optic sensors are commonly used in microsensor formats as single fiber, or bundled fibers. Fiber optics are capable of transmitting light over long distances and multiplexing, but can be subject to background absorbance, fluorescence/Raman scattering, and diffraction effects.
From Soup: 32 Many fiber optic probe sensors utilize a luminophore immobilized at the tip of the fiber(s). 46,49 The luminophore is excited, emission of photons is monitored using a photodetector ( e.g. , photodiode or photomultiplier tube), and transduced into a voltage signal. Changes in the measured emission of photons due to the presence of target molecule(s) are recorded ( e.g. , via intensity or lifetime) and correlated to analyte concentration near the probe tip. Intensity-based measurements can be prone to calibration drift due to photobleaching. 50 Ratiometric approaches are used to significantly improve relaibility, 10 but to date have not been used in SR modality. Frequency domain lifetime approaches increase the efficiency of lifetime based measurements. 50
 ###### 
From cou.: 33 Many fiber optic probe sensors utilize a luminophore immobilized at the tip of the fiber(s).46,49 The luminophore is excited, emission of photons is monitored using a photodetector (e.g., photodiode or photomultiplier tube), and transduced into a voltage signal. Changes in the measured emission of photons due to the presence of target molecule(s) are recorded (e.g., via intensity or lifetime) and correlated to analyte concentration near the probe tip. Intensity-based measurements can be prone to calibration drift due to photobleaching.50 Ratiometric approaches are used to significantly improve relaibility,10 but to date have not been used in SR modality. Frequency domain lifetime approaches increase the efficiency of lifetime based measurements.50
From Soup: 33 An optical microsensor (or optrode) utilizing the oxygen-quenched phosphorescent dye (platinum tetrakis pentafluorophenyl porphyrin, or PtFPP) is depicted in Fig. 4 . The dye is immobilized on the tip of a tapered fiber optic cable within a polystyrene membrane (also containing photocatalysts such as titanium dioxide). Excitation of the luminophore causes photon absorption (changing energy state from ground to the excited state). Energy is lost by excited molecules during the luminophore lifetime, resulting in the release of photons ( i.e. , emission). Emission is monitored using a photomultiplier tube and lock-in amplifier , and changes in measured phase angle are used to quantify the concentration of oxygen near the sensor tip. In the presence of oxygen, luminescence is quenched, reducing emission according to the Stern–Volmer relationship.
 ###### 
From cou.: 34 An optical microsensor (or optrode) utilizing the oxygen-quenched phosphorescent dye (platinum tetrakis pentafluorophenyl porphyrin, or PtFPP) is depicted in Fig. 4. The dye is immobilized on the tip of a tapered fiber optic cable within a polystyrene membrane (also containing photocatalysts such as titanium dioxide). Excitation of the luminophore causes photon absorption (changing energy state from ground to the excited state). Energy is lost by excited molecules during the luminophore lifetime, resulting in the release of photons (i.e., emission). Emission is monitored using a photomultiplier tube and lock-in amplifier, and changes in measured phase angle are used to quantify the concentration of oxygen near the sensor tip. In the presence of oxygen, luminescence is quenched, reducing emission according to the Stern–Volmer relationship.
From Soup: 34 There are a number of approaches for fabricating optrodes, and readers are referred to the literature for fabricating luminophore microoptrodes described herein. 46,47,49,50 Materials such as silica nanospheres, titanium dioxide, barium sulfate, copper oxide, gold, lead oxide , and zinc sulfide have been used to increase the fluorescence intensity ( i.e. , scattering) in various optrode configurations. 46–47,49,50
 ###### 
From cou.: 35 There are a number of approaches for fabricating optrodes, and readers are referred to the literature for fabricating luminophore microoptrodes described herein.46,47,49,50 Materials such as silica nanospheres, titanium dioxide, barium sulfate, copper oxide, gold, lead oxide, and zinc sulfide have been used to increase the fluorescence intensity (i.e., scattering) in various optrode configurations.46–47,49,50
From Soup: 35 SR hardware is described in detail in the literature. 20,26,29,31 Briefly, hardware includes a vibration isolation table with Faraday cage (Technical Manufacturing Co., Peabody. MA), camera/zoomscope and sensor(s) mounted on a head stage controlled by a motion control system (MCS). Automated Scanning Electrode Technique (ASET) software is used for data acquisition (A/D) and control functions (D/A) (Science Wares, Falmouth, MA). A/D boards with DC-coupled differential amplifiers, low/high pass filters, and video/data acquisition systems are available through Applicable Electronics, Inc. (Sandwich, MA) ( Fig. 1A ).
 ###### 
From cou.: 36 SR hardware is described in detail in the literature.20,26,29,31 Briefly, hardware includes a vibration isolation table with Faraday cage (Technical Manufacturing Co., Peabody. MA), camera/zoomscope and sensor(s) mounted on a head stage controlled by a motion control system (MCS). Automated Scanning Electrode Technique (ASET) software is used for data acquisition (A/D) and control functions (D/A) (Science Wares, Falmouth, MA). A/D boards with DC-coupled differential amplifiers, low/high pass filters, and video/data acquisition systems are available through Applicable Electronics, Inc. (Sandwich, MA) (Fig. 1A).
From Soup: 36 During operation, computer controlled movement of the sensor induces a phase dependant waveform on the output signal, and amplitude of this signal is proportional to the differential analyte concentration. The signal from the preamplifier head stage is capacitively coupled through a lock-in amplifier to discretely subtract baseline output signal (bath offset) so that the differential waveform can be amplified to digitally analyze differential signals. To avoid capacitive decay in the 0.1–0.5 Hz time domain (leading to an underestimation of the true flux), baseline signals are discretely subtracted (DC coupling) prior to amplification. DC-coupling allows for baseline subtraction without differential signal degradation due to capacitive discharge, allowing calculation of concentration differentials without making assumptions regarding background signals and measurement efficiency. 21
 ###### 
From cou.: 37 During operation, computer controlled movement of the sensor induces a phase dependant waveform on the output signal, and amplitude of this signal is proportional to the differential analyte concentration. The signal from the preamplifier head stage is capacitively coupled through a lock-in amplifier to discretely subtract baseline output signal (bath offset) so that the differential waveform can be amplified to digitally analyze differential signals. To avoid capacitive decay in the 0.1–0.5 Hz time domain (leading to an underestimation of the true flux), baseline signals are discretely subtracted (DC coupling) prior to amplification. DC-coupling allows for baseline subtraction without differential signal degradation due to capacitive discharge, allowing calculation of concentration differentials without making assumptions regarding background signals and measurement efficiency.21
