From cou.: 40 Self-referencing potentiometry.
From Soup: 40 For SR potentiometric (ion-selective) electrodes, the Fick equation is combined with the Nernst or Nikolsky–Eisenmann equation, and simplified to eqn (5) . Upon calculation of Δ E , the E o and K pot terms from the Nikolsky–Eisenmann equation cancel, and measured potential is a function of primary ion activity and Nernst slope (s). where: J = primary ion flux [μmol cm −2 s −1 ], E ( x ) = electrode potential at near pole [mV], E ( x +Δ x ) = electrode potential at far pole [mV], and b = y -intercept of Nernst calibration plot [mV].
 ###### 
From cou.: 41 For SR potentiometric (ion-selective) electrodes, the Fick equation is combined with the Nernst or Nikolsky–Eisenmann equation, and simplified to eqn (5). Upon calculation of ΔE, the Eo and Kpot terms from the Nikolsky–Eisenmann equation cancel, and measured potential is a function of primary ion activity and Nernst slope (s).where: J = primary ion flux [μmol cm−2 s−1], E(x) = electrode potential at near pole [mV], E(x+Δx) = electrode potential at far pole [mV], and b = y-intercept of Nernst calibration plot [mV].
From Soup: 41 For SR oxygen optrode analysis using phosphorescent dyes , the equation describing Δ C based on phase angle measurements at the near pole and far pole is: where: ϕ 1 = phase angle at near pole, ϕ 2 = phase angle at far pole, b = slope of calibration plot (0–21% oxygen).
 ###### 
From cou.: 42 For SR oxygen optrode analysis using phosphorescent dyes, the equation describing ΔC based on phase angle measurements at the near pole and far pole is:where: ϕ1 = phase angle at near pole, ϕ2 = phase angle at far pole, b = slope of calibration plot (0–21% oxygen).
From Soup: 42 Concentration calibration of micro/nanosensors is conducted using common methods described in the literature. 21,26,37 The major parameters governing SR microsensor efficiency are sensor sensitivity and oscillation frequency. Sensitivity is a function of response time, active surface area, and transduction/acquisition type. Oscillation protocol is a function of size (tip diameter), response time, and the excursion distance (Δ X ) over which the sensor is translated. Prior to use in biological experiments, oscillation frequency must be optimized to maximize sensor translation without inducing stirring. For microsensors with tip diameters in the 800 nm to 5 μm range, the range suggested by Kühtreiber and Jaffe 23 (between 0.20 and 0.50 Hz) is valid. For most cell/tissue transport studies, the thickness of the mass boundary layer formed at the bulk liquid-cell/tissue interface is approximately 50 μm to 1 mm. 32 To fall within the 0.2–0.5 Hz time domain, sensor response time ( t 95 ) should be less than 2.0 s, and the excursion distance should not be larger than approximately 100 μm. As a general rule of thumb, the excursion distance should not be greater than 10% of the thickness of the mass boundary layer (see Fig. 5 for details).
 ###### 
From cou.: 43 Concentration calibration of micro/nanosensors is conducted using common methods described in the literature.21,26,37 The major parameters governing SR microsensor efficiency are sensor sensitivity and oscillation frequency. Sensitivity is a function of response time, active surface area, and transduction/acquisition type. Oscillation protocol is a function of size (tip diameter), response time, and the excursion distance (ΔX) over which the sensor is translated. Prior to use in biological experiments, oscillation frequency must be optimized to maximize sensor translation without inducing stirring. For microsensors with tip diameters in the 800 nm to 5 μm range, the range suggested by Kühtreiber and Jaffe23 (between 0.20 and 0.50 Hz) is valid. For most cell/tissue transport studies, the thickness of the mass boundary layer formed at the bulk liquid-cell/tissue interface is approximately 50 μm to 1 mm.32 To fall within the 0.2–0.5 Hz time domain, sensor response time (t95) should be less than 2.0 s, and the excursion distance should not be larger than approximately 100 μm. As a general rule of thumb, the excursion distance should not be greater than 10% of the thickness of the mass boundary layer (see Fig. 5 for details).
From Soup: 43 To optimize oscillation frequency, abiotic microprofiling experiments are conducted, and compared to simple diffusion-reaction models. A stable abiotic concentration gradient can be produced by mixing a solution containing the target analyte with a dilute polymer solution ( e.g. , ≈1% agar, alginate, sol gel), and injecting the mixture into a glass micropipette. The filled pipette is placed into a bath solution simulating that to be used in the biological experiment, and a concentration gradient allowed to develop near the open tip of the pipette (typically within 20–40 min). A SR microsensor is positioned ≈1 μm from the open micropipette tip using a stepper motor-video zoomscope apparatus. The sensor is oscillated in the direction of transport (perpendicular to the tangent of the pipette tip), and Δ C /Δ X continuously recorded. Flux within the concentration gradient near the pipette tip is profiled, and compared to a simple one or two dimensional empirical diffusion model (the simplest case uses a non-reactive analyte). The correlation between the measured and predicted flux ( ϕ ) is used as a validation of the SR sensor under controlled abiotic conditions. This set of experiments is critical in validating the use of new SR microsensor designs, and it is recommended the correlation between measured and predicted flux is at least 0.90.
 ###### 
From cou.: 44 To optimize oscillation frequency, abiotic microprofiling experiments are conducted, and compared to simple diffusion-reaction models. A stable abiotic concentration gradient can be produced by mixing a solution containing the target analyte with a dilute polymer solution (e.g., ≈1% agar, alginate, sol gel), and injecting the mixture into a glass micropipette. The filled pipette is placed into a bath solution simulating that to be used in the biological experiment, and a concentration gradient allowed to develop near the open tip of the pipette (typically within 20–40 min). A SR microsensor is positioned ≈1 μm from the open micropipette tip using a stepper motor-video zoomscope apparatus. The sensor is oscillated in the direction of transport (perpendicular to the tangent of the pipette tip), and ΔC/ΔX continuously recorded. Flux within the concentration gradient near the pipette tip is profiled, and compared to a simple one or two dimensional empirical diffusion model (the simplest case uses a non-reactive analyte). The correlation between the measured and predicted flux (ϕ) is used as a validation of the SR sensor under controlled abiotic conditions. This set of experiments is critical in validating the use of new SR microsensor designs, and it is recommended the correlation between measured and predicted flux is at least 0.90.
From Soup: 44 For the above example of the source pipette, predictive models can be developed by assuming isotropic radial diffusion from the pipette tip. Using known distance-concentration profiles, values of flux ( D *Δ C /Δ X ) can be predicted at any spatial location within the gradient. An additional parameter describing abiotic reaction phenomena ( e.g. , sorption , chelation) can be added to these predictive models if desired.
 ###### 
From cou.: 45 For the above example of the source pipette, predictive models can be developed by assuming isotropic radial diffusion from the pipette tip. Using known distance-concentration profiles, values of flux (D*ΔC/ΔX) can be predicted at any spatial location within the gradient. An additional parameter describing abiotic reaction phenomena (e.g., sorption, chelation) can be added to these predictive models if desired.
From Soup: 45 One and two dimensional microprofiles of abiotic flux are shown in Fig. 5 . In Fig. 5a , one dimensional Ca + 2 efflux was measured from a capillary filled with 10 mM CaCl 2 in a bath solution of PBS , and also in a bath solution of PBS + 10 mm EDTA. As expected, the Ca 2+ efflux from the pipette in the solution of PBS was significantly greater than the efflux in a bath solution of 100 mM EDTA ( p < 0.01, α = 0.05) due to the chelation of free calcium by EDTA. Fig. 5b demonstrates two dimensional microprofiling of Ag + efflux from a capillary filled with 1 mM AgNO 3 and agarose using the techniques in McLamore et al. , 51 which correlated well with predicted values.
 ###### 
From cou.: 46 One and two dimensional microprofiles of abiotic flux are shown in Fig. 5. In Fig. 5a, one dimensional Ca+2 efflux was measured from a capillary filled with 10 mM CaCl2 in a bath solution of PBS, and also in a bath solution of PBS + 10 mm EDTA. As expected, the Ca2+ efflux from the pipette in the solution of PBS was significantly greater than the efflux in a bath solution of 100 mM EDTA (p < 0.01, α = 0.05) due to the chelation of free calcium by EDTA. Fig. 5b demonstrates two dimensional microprofiling of Ag+ efflux from a capillary filled with 1 mM AgNO3 and agarose using the techniques in McLamore et al.,51 which correlated well with predicted values.
From Soup: 46 In additional to optimizing oscillation frequency, microprofiling experiments are used to calculate the distance of the mass boundary layer ( δ ) formed between the bulk liquid and the surface of the analyte source/sink. The δ is defined as the spatial location where the flux is less than 99% of the maximum boundary layer flux. The value of δ provides direct information about rate limiting transport kinetics, and may be combined with measurement of momentum/thermal boundary layer(s), aiding in the development of dynamic models. 26,31,32 Note that in Fig. 5A the excursion distance (30 μm) is less than 10% of the thickness of the mass boundary layer (515 μm), ensuring that the change in concentration over Δ X is approximately linear (and Fick's 1st Law is applicable).
 ###### 
From cou.: 47 In additional to optimizing oscillation frequency, microprofiling experiments are used to calculate the distance of the mass boundary layer (δ) formed between the bulk liquid and the surface of the analyte source/sink. The δ is defined as the spatial location where the flux is less than 99% of the maximum boundary layer flux. The value of δ provides direct information about rate limiting transport kinetics, and may be combined with measurement of momentum/thermal boundary layer(s), aiding in the development of dynamic models.26,31,32 Note that in Fig. 5A the excursion distance (30 μm) is less than 10% of the thickness of the mass boundary layer (515 μm), ensuring that the change in concentration over ΔX is approximately linear (and Fick's 1st Law is applicable).
From Soup: 47 An additional consideration when using SR ion-selective microelectrodes is the presence of buffers within the bulk media. Porterfield et al. 52 presented a method for measuring proton flux in buffered media using SR microelectrodes. The calculation depends on known values of the total buffer concentration and the p K a . A physical constant known as the linear buffering coefficient is then used with the assumption that the experiment is conducted within 2.0 pH units of the p K a ( i.e. , within the linear portion of pH speciation curve). where: Δ[H + ] = measured change in H + [nM], B t = total buffer concentration [M], LBC = linear buffering coefficient (0.0025), and K a = dissociation constant for buffer .
 ###### 
From cou.: 48 An additional consideration when using SR ion-selective microelectrodes is the presence of buffers within the bulk media. Porterfield et al.52 presented a method for measuring proton flux in buffered media using SR microelectrodes. The calculation depends on known values of the total buffer concentration and the pKa. A physical constant known as the linear buffering coefficient is then used with the assumption that the experiment is conducted within 2.0 pH units of the pKa (i.e., within the linear portion of pH speciation curve).where: Δ[H+] = measured change in H+ [nM], Bt = total buffer concentration [M], LBC = linear buffering coefficient (0.0025), and Ka = dissociation constant for buffer.
From Soup: 48 When characterizing differential signals which are in the sub nV to μV range, temporal concentration drift due to cellular activity can produce erroneous results. 38 For example, if the surface concentration is continuously changing over time, values of Δ C calculated using the C ( x ) minus C ( x +Δ x ) technique ( eqn (2)–(4) ) may produce drift artifacts (positive drift leading to negative differential artifact). In such a case, a simple signal post-processing technique is used. The digital differential filtering (DDF) technique removes signals associated with temporal drift while leaving differential signals intact. The DDF algorithm filters signals every half cycle using eqn (6) , where C ( x ) n is the near pole concentration for measurement cycle n , and C ( x ) n +1 is the near pole concentration for measurement cycle n + 1. 31,35
 ###### 
From cou.: 49 When characterizing differential signals which are in the sub nV to μV range, temporal concentration drift due to cellular activity can produce erroneous results.38 For example, if the surface concentration is continuously changing over time, values of ΔC calculated using the C(x) minus C(x+Δx) technique (eqn (2)–(4)) may produce drift artifacts (positive drift leading to negative differential artifact). In such a case, a simple signal post-processing technique is used. The digital differential filtering (DDF) technique removes signals associated with temporal drift while leaving differential signals intact. The DDF algorithm filters signals every half cycle using eqn (6), where C(x)n is the near pole concentration for measurement cycle n, and C(x)n+1 is the near pole concentration for measurement cycle n + 1.31,35
